<br>
(OOC: Warning, this is a dark, harsh and somewhat brutal story, but I thought appropriate for the character.  If something like this might bother you, please don't read it.  However, I have kept it clean and while it is mature, it is not adult.)<br>
_____________________<br>
<br>
“A dozen lousy copper?”<br>
<br>
The pain started as a stinging shock, followed by numbness.  A dull aching warmth spread across the left side of her face.  The little girl stumbled and fell to the floor from the blow.  When she looked up, tears trickled down her dirt-smudged cheeks leaving small clean streaks.  A bit of blood oozed slowly from a split lip.  Father was angry.<br>
<br>
“Oh, now you cry?” he yelled the girl.  “Why don’t you try that out there, where it might do some good?  Squeeze out a few of those tears and you might get me a little more money.  But, no!  This is what I get?  Twelve copper?  You‘ll get back out there and don‘t come back until you got a few silver!”<br>
<br>
Her eyes flickered from her father, to the table that occupied one corner of the small, dirty room.  Remains of a meal, a crust of bread, something in a bowl, were growing stale and cold.  She looked to the door that led outside and then back to her father again, hoping he hadn’t noticed.  Staggering across the room, he grabbed the girl roughly and slammed her against the wall.  His breathe stank of ale, as usual, but also of dinner.  Her stomach growled.<br>
<br>
“You want something to eat?”  Another slap and her lip bled more.  She knew she had to get out quickly, or he would start using his fists.  “You bring me copper and you want food?”  <br>
<br>
He pulled her from the wall and shoved her roughly toward the door.  She stumbled, but didn’t fall.  That would only make him mad.  No use explaining how another kid had beat her up and stolen what she had begged that day, that the twelve copper was all she’d been able to get after that.  Words only made him mad.  Crying only made him mad.  Theresa began to think that her just being around made him mad.<br>
<br>
She darted out the door into the darkness of early night.<br>
____________________________________________<br>
<br>
“Gimme your money, girl.”<br>
<br>
The older kid sneered at her.  He had to be at least thirteen and easily weighed twice what she did.  He was dirty, and his grin showed several missing teeth.  Theresa wanted to run.  She’d escaped him a couple of times before.  Not today, though.  <br>
<br>
“Sympathy!  I told you, make ’em cry, feel sorry for you,” her father had said earlier.  He had used his hands again, until she was crying.  Then, he had stepped down hard on her foot.  Something had snapped and pain had exploded from the injured foot, dizzying her.  “There.  If you can’t fake a limp, I’ll give you one for real.”<br>
<br>
She tried to run, hobbling a few painful steps before the boy caught up and shoved her to the ground.  His fists rained down on her until she stopped struggling.  Planting his knee in her back, he rummaged through her clothes for the change she had tried to hide.  The old, tattered dress only had a couple of pockets and he found the money easily.<br>
<br>
“Oh, holding out on me, today.  Three silver!” he cackled happily.<br>
<br>
Theresa lay in the dirt after he had left, bitter tears dropping onto the dusty ground.  Her nose bled freely.  People passed her, but no one said anything, no one offered a hand to help.  This was East Freeport after all, and you kept to your own business.   Finally, she pulled herself up and slumped against the nearby stone wall.<br>
<br>
That’s when she first saw him.<br>
<br>
Across the open square, another beggar walked toward her.  After a moment, though, she knew he wasn’t a beggar.  Dark eyes burned beneath the hood of his cloak, watching her with contempt.  His clothes were tattered but he moved with an air of authority, though only one who really lived on the streets could tell the difference.  No sympathy on that dark face.  It was as if he enjoyed watching her pain.  Stopping next to her, he dropped a dirty rag in her lap.  Theresa picked it up, holding it to her nose.<br>
<br>
“Is life always this hard,” she asked him, “or is it just when you’re a kid?”<br>
<br>
He stared hard for a moment, then said, “Always like this.”<br>
<br>
The moment passed.  The man only shook his head before walking on.<br>
_______________________________________<br>
<br>
The Temple of Marr was an amazing structure, towering over her.  It made her feel small, but in a way different than what she was used to.  Passing through North Freeport had also been strange.  It was so clean, and the building were solidly build and not rotting or falling apart.  She felt dirty and out of place, and from some of the looks of passers-by she knew others thought the same.  Normally, Theresa would never enter this part of the city, even if the paladin guards would allow a dirty beggar child to do so.  Today, though, was different.<br>
<br>
The priestess of Erollisi stood beside her, smiling down at the child’s awkward wonder.  Several other children from the streets gathered around, also having followed the woman who had offered them a warm meal.  In exchange for the food, they only had to listen to the words of the lady.<br>
<br>
She waited her time in the line, and took the food that was given.  So much!  A bowl of some sort of soup, with real meat in it.  Fresh bread, not stale and no trace of mold that she could see.  A small square of cheese and a glass of milk.  After sitting down and gazing in amazement, she hurriedly tore off most of the bread and crammed it in a pocket.  Something for later.<br>
<br>
“Good idea, girl,” said a familiar voice.<br>
<br>
The mean boy slid in next to her on the bench, grinning.  Theresa looked around, hoping someone would see and help, but the priests and their helpers were busy with their other tasks.  He grabbed her leg under the table and pinched hard.  <br>
<br>
“You just shut up and sit still,” he told her.  “Don’t you eat any of that, either.  That’s my food.  Thanks for watching it for me.”  She started to protest, but the boy pinched harder.  “You make any noise and next time I see you on the street, I won’t be as nice as I usually am.”  Theresa quieted and sat still, then nodded.<br>
<br>
The sermon came and the priestess stood before them, speaking of the Twins.  Perhaps some of the children listened, wolfing down the food that was before them.  Theresa pretended to listen, but the words fell on deaf ears.  Her eyes looked longingly to the bowl before her, but she didn’t eat.  When the boy finished his own food, and no one was looking, he switched his empty plate with hers and kept munching and slurping noisily.  She didn’t cry, though.  That would just bring attention, and that would make him mad.<br>
<br>
So she sat and as the lady spoke of love and truth, the little girl just listened to her own stomach rumbling with hunger.<br>
__________<br>
<br>
Theresa hugged herself, tightly, trembling.  It was turning cold as the sun fell tonight.  She had a bit of money, and she had evaded the boy today.  Maybe she could buy a crust of bread for a copper before going home.  Father wouldn’t miss that.  Well, miss it or not, he’d hit her anyway.  She didn’t have to do anything wrong for that.<br>
<br>
Across the square, a priest of life walked by, resplendent in his robes.  Going to the docks, perhaps, to the story-like continent of Faydwer where gnomes, dwarves and elves lived.  He cared nothing for her plight, she knew.  They only took in and fed the kids from time to time to make themselves feel better.  For the children of East Freeport, though, it just served as an occasional reminder of what they didn’t and would probably never have.  She glared at the priest’s back as he disappeared down the street.  She hated them.<br>
<br>
“How much did you get for me today, girl?” the voice came.<br>
<br>
Theresa bolted.  It wasn’t fast enough.  It usually never was.  She was in the dirt again, his fists pummeling her back and arms.  I almost made it, she thought.  It’s not fair.  Finally, she went limp, giving in again.  Hatred filled her, for the priests, who were never around when this happened … for the boy, taking what she begged and scrounged all day for … for her father and the beating that she knew would come tonight.  Something snapped.<br>
<br>
When the boy rolled her over to search her, Theresa’s fingers scrabbled in the dirt.  A handful of dust flew into the boy’s face.  He looked startled at first.  She had never fought back.  Then, he yelped as the dirt stung his eyes and he put his fists up to them, rubbing.  Theresa scrambled from underneath him, and as she was almost free she raised her leg and shoved her foot as hard as she could into his groin.<br>
<br>
The boy gasped, drawing in breath and slumping over the ground beside her.  He curled into a ball and moaned.  Theresa clumsily gained her feet and stepped away from where he writhed.  She felt good.  He was the one crying this time.  She started to run away, to get home before he came to, and the thought entered her mind.<br>
<br>
What’s he going to do when he finds me tomorrow?  He will find me.  He always does.  He’s hurt now, but he won’t be next time.  He’ll be ready.  He’ll hurt me.  Maybe bad.<br>
<br>
Her eyes darted around, her mind raced.  The boy wasn’t moaning anymore, just huddled up on the ground.  He’d be getting up soon.  She looked at him, looked around again.<br>
<br>
A rock.  It was big.  Theresa squatted and grabbed it, tearing a couple of fingernails loose as she shoved her fingers underneath it.  The pain was fresh, but it didn’t distract her.  Instinct had taken over.  Survival.<br>
<br>
She lifted the rock, straining, and picked it up to rest against her chest.  The boy was starting to move again.  She looked at him, looked at the rock, became worried.  What am I doing?  Then, the memories came to her.  Stolen food, bruises, her father’s anger, hunger … and hate.  <br>
<br>
The rock came down. <br>
<br>
There was a horrible noise when it hit him, and an even more horrible one he made.  He stopped trying to get up though, and just lay there.  Theresa looked around to see who might be watching. <br>
<br>
Aside from the usual street trash, they were alone.  The boy moaned and she kicked him.  There was no pity in her, no thought of what she was doing, only her dismal rage and the hatred that burned through her blood, warming her despite the chill night.  I’ve hurt him, but if he gets away, or someone helps him, someday he’ll be back.  He'll hurt me again.<br>
<br>
She picked up the rock.  Three more times and he stopped moving completely.  She wasn't sure why she kept hitting him after that.  It just made her feel good.<br>
___________________<br>
<br>
A couple of years passed.<br>
<br>
Theresa was growing up.  She felt and saw the changes, small as they were.   Her body was at times awkward, an enemy with new problems she had to find a way to overcome.  There was no mother to ask, no woman who might help that she would go to.  So, she stumbled into adolescence alone, her only teacher experience.<br>
<br>
No one had bothered her since the incident with the rock.  Some of the other boys on the street began to look at her differently, though.  Even some of the men, on their way to taverns or guards on duty.  It was an uncomfortable look, and she knew it had something to do with the changes.  Something to do with the women who frequented the taverns and went upstairs with men.  Theresa was sure she didn’t want to know more than that.<br>
<br>
Her father grew more drunk and more angry.  He rarely bothered slapping her anymore, instead just using his fists and sometimes his feet when she fell.  She was sure he hated her, though probably not as much as she knew she hated him.  She also knew one of these days, he would kill her.  Or maybe worse.  He had started looking at her differently, too.<br>
________________________<br>
<br>
“Lousy couple of silver?” he screamed.<br>
<br>
It was never enough anymore.  It didn’t matter how much she brought him, it was never enough.  The punch sent her to her knees and she felt the blood trickle from her nose.  She held a hand to it, to keep from bleeding all over herself and the floor.  Blood on her clothes meant less money on the street.  Blood on the floor … would only bring more blood.  Maybe he’ll make my eyes swell shut again, she thought, then I won’t have to look at him.  Maybe he’ll kill me.  At least it’ll be over.<br>
<br>
“Not bringin’ in the money anymore, girl,” he said.  He’d never called her by name in as long as she could remember.  He probably didn’t even know it anymore.  “Getting’ too old, people like givin’ money to kids.  Makes ’em feel good.”<br>
<br>
She sat up against the wall, looking at the ground.  You didn’t meet his eyes when he was mad, unless he told you to.   He grew quiet and that scared her.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, softly, he muttered, “Maybe it’s time.”<br>
<br>
She did look up at that.<br>
<br>
“You’re older now, not a kid anymore,” he said, looking nervous for once.  “There’s people, men … in the taverns and such.  They’d give you good money, better’n what you get on the streets.”<br>
<br>
It took a moment for what he was saying to dawn on her.  He wanted her to be like those other older girls and women.  The ones with the hollow eyes and fake smiles.  The ones that went upstairs with the sweaty drunks.  She shook her head, without realizing it.<br>
<br>
“No!” he screamed.  “You telling’ me no?  I’m your father, and you’ll damned well do what I tell you to do, you lazy brat.  If you can’t bring in your share on the street, you’ll bring it on your ..”<br>
<br>
“I won’t,” she screamed back at him.<br>
<br>
Minutes later, she lay sobbing on the floor.  It was the worst ever.  She felt her left eye swelling, blood flowing from her nose, lip and split cheek.  She thought her arm might be broken.  When she tried to get up, the pain that shot through it was so strong that she almost vomited, but instead passed out.  When she came to again, he was sitting in the chair at the table watching her.  Drinking.<br>
<br>
“You’ll do it,” he told her quietly.  “Or I’ll have to hurt you.  Not gentle like this, but bad.   Now do something useful and clean this place up.”<br>
<br>
He staggered off into the other room.  When she heard him fall into his bed, Theresa slowly got to her feet, careful with the bad arm.  She refused to cry.  There was no one to help her, no one to turn to that wouldn’t be just as bad.  This was her home.  Without it, she’d be living on the street and that was worse.  She saw what sometimes happened to people that slept on the street.  She had to keep her home, just … without him.<br>
<br>
Her mind wandered, as her body went through the motions of cleaning.  I hate him, she thought.  He’s going to kill me.  Or worse.  She cleared the table, instinct taking over while she tried to figure out what she could do.  It was half clean when her hand came across the knife.  The old, rusty knife that father ate with.  He’d once poked her with it, repeatedly, when she’d been sick and said she couldn’t go out and beg.  Just poked her, over and over, until she had stopped screaming, stopped crying, and did what he wanted.   Her fingers closed around it.<br>
<br>
You’ll do it, she heard him say.  She shivered.  <br>
<br>
“No,” she said softly to herself.  “I won’t.”<br>
<br>
Theresa walked into the bedroom and shut the door.<br>
_________________________________________<br>
<br>
She wandered aimlessly from the house.  Vague memories darted around her mind.  A mother, no face, just a warm feeling.  Was that love?  Father, not drunk and dirty, not angry, giving her a piece of candy that he’d brought home for her.  He worked hard at the docks, but he’d remembered her birthday.  Back before things got bad, back before the drinking had started.<br>
<br>
Theresa put her face in her hands, sticky and warm with blood, and wept softly.  The memories flowed through her and as they did, they disappeared.  The warmth, the happiness, the love … remembered briefly, and then gone.  There was no room in this world for those memories, those emotions.  They only got you hurt … or worse.<br>
<br>
Is this what dying feels like?, she wondered.  Part of her was dying.  She struggled briefly, holding onto it with desperation, but then, finally, let go.  It wasn’t worth holding onto.  I will not cry any more.  Instead, she felt the coldness, rage and the hatred, the things that had saved her more than once.  Her strengths.  She embraced them.  Looking at her hands, her clothes, spattered and stained with her father’s blood.<br>
<br>
Theresa smiled.<br>
<br>
The low side of East Freeport was even worse than the rest of the area and the few people around moved away quickly, ignoring the bloody girl to the best of their ability.  Something about her even kept away those that would usually try to prey on a girl injured such as she was.  One of her eyes had swollen shut as she knew it would and she blindly made her way back to the house.<br>
<br>
That’s when she ran into him.<br>
<br>
He looked at her with the same contempt he’d given her before, years before.  The man in the cloak, with the dark eyes.  His hands grabbed her by the arms and stopped her.  Pain shot through her broken arm and she almost fainted, so he slapped her.  That did it.<br>
<br>
Theresa glared at him.  The tears were gone, the fear, too.  No one would ever hurt her again.  Only rage remained.  “Hit me again and I will kill you,” she told him.<br>
<br>
The man chuckled.  “Good … that’s what I was looking for.”<br>
<br>
Theresa turned away to leave, toward the old, run down building.  To the room that was her home.  The man stopped her, his one hand never leaving her arm.  The grip was powerful, his aura of authority too much to deny.  She looked back at him.<br>
<br>
“That’s not your home any more,” he told her.  &quot;That stopped being your home when you caved in that boy's skull.&quot;<br>
<br>
That got her attention.<br>
<br>
So, Theresa followed him, still angry, but curious now.  Something was happening, had been happening since the moment she lifted the rock over that boy’s head.   They arrived before another run-down building, walked inside.  She looked at him, questioningly.<br>
<br>
“This is your new home, girl,” he told her.<br>
<br>
“My name is Theresa.”<br>
<br>
A small chuckle again, and he replied.  “Theresa it is, then.  I am Pietro Zarn.  This is home.  This is the Dismal Rage.  There’s dried food in that crate over there.  Water in that barrel.  There’s cots and rolls on the floor.  Get cleaned, then eat and sleep.  One of the clerics will be up shortly to see to that arm.  Save your questions for tomorrow, when we start your training.”<br>
<br>
“Training?” she wondered.<br>
<br>
Pietro looked to her again, dark eyes dancing wickedly.  “When I will teach you what hate really is, girl.&quot;  After a pause, he added, &quot;Theresa.”<br>
<br>
Then, he left her alone to wonder what the next day would bring.<br>
_________________________________________________<br>
<br>
