<br>
&quot;Pathetic.&quot;<br>
<br>
The voice sneered as her blow was deflected.  The counterattack took her squarely across the jaw, splitting open the flesh and shattering bone.  The sheer force of it spun her roughly to the dirt floor.  She didn't cry out.  Theresa was used to pain.  She spit blood into the dust and was unsurprised to see a couple of teeth.  Blood ran freely down her neck and spattered the floor.<br>
<br>
&quot;Am I done with the street rat?  Can I have a real opponent?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Again,&quot; another voice, deeper and rougher, stated curtly.  Brutol Rhaksen was overseeing training for the Dismal Rage.  The battle-scarred warrior was without pity.  She was glad.  She didn't want pity.  She wanted to make Wendel scream.<br>
<br>
Shakily, she regained her footing.  A glance around and she picked up her weapon.  The short sword was old and rusted.  Her armor was a mismatched patchwork of animal hides.  Wendel Vaughn stood across the circle from her, dressed head to toe in plate armor made of some dull gray metal.  Acrylia, she'd heard him boasting to another trainee.  She didn't know what it was, only that it made hurting him almost impossible.  To make things worse, he already had the best basic combat training that his North Freeport merchant parents could buy.<br>
<br>
Wendel, either sensing her thoughts, or just being condescending as always, grinned at her.  &quot;Give up.  You'll never be a warrior, little girl.  But, if you let the cleric fix that pretty face up ... I might just let you be my whore.&quot;<br>
<br>
The words had barely left his mouth and Theresa was on him.  Blow after blow rained down on his armor.  Some were deflected by his shield, others parried on his sword.  The few that made it through his defenses were still unable to find a vulnerable spot.  Her fury continued until a swing was deflected wide and left her completely open.  His shield slammed into her face.  Her nose splintered, sending pain through her entire head, blinding her.  Before she could recover, she felt his blade running her through.<br>
<br>
Gut wound.  <br>
<br>
He'd done it on purpose.  The agony was indescribable.  He twisted the blade.  Theresa screamed and fell to her knees.  Then, the sickening, strange sensation followed as he slowly pulled the machete-looking sword from her.  Theresa slumped to the dirt and coughed up blood.<br>
<br>
Her vision went from red to black as consciousness faded.  The last thing she heard was Brutol's harsh voice finally calling for the cleric.<br>
____________________________________________________<br>
<br>
&quot;What?&quot;<br>
<br>
Pietro's was calm, as always.  Theresa had yet to see anything that broke his demeanor.  Hers, on the other hand, had snapped.  She yelled, angrily.<br>
<br>
&quot;I said it's not fair.  Why the hell did Rhaksen send me up against Wendel?  He's an advanced student, he knows how to fight.  I was doing just fine in basics.&quot;<br>
<br>
She paced in front of him.  A small girl, Theresa was barely as high as her mentor's breastbone.  That petite frame was unable to express the pent up rage inside her, so she paced as she talked, fists slamming on open air to emphasize certain points.<br>
<br>
&quot;I can handle my own with any of those others,&quot; she continued.  &quot;I mean, I've got the crappy armor that was dug out of a closet and I had to stitch it down just to fit me.  He's got acrylia!  What the hell is acrylia?  I can't get my piece of shit short sword through it, that’s for sure, but he has no problem running me through with that sendy machete thing ...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Centi,&quot; Zarn interrupted.  Theresa paused.  &quot;Centi short sword.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't care what it's called, I just care that it goes through my armor like butter and ...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Shut up,&quot; he said, casually.<br>
<br>
Theresa stopped again, looking at him.  Her face was red with anger.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shut up?  You give me a combat teacher that gets off on my pain and throws me up against someone I can't hope to beat.  What the hell was he thinking when he ..&quot;<br>
<br>
The backhand knocked her down.  Pietro Zarn stared coldly at her as she stood back up and met his eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;I said shut up,&quot; he stated.  &quot;I’m the teacher. You are the student.  You don't like what I'm teaching, walk out.  I'm sure you'll make a good living as a thief or a ...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Don't!&quot; she shouted.<br>
<br>
&quot;What?  Whore?&quot; he sneered.  &quot;What is it about that word that bothers you so much?  It's just a word, used to punch whatever buttons make you go off.  Yes, Brutol sent you up against a better trained student.  I told him to!  I even suggested to Vaughn what to say to you.  Not that he needed it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Theresa was stunned.  &quot;Why?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Because you have no focus,&quot; he said.  There was some passion in his voice and that, more than any way he'd spoke before, frightened her.  &quot;I've seen such hate in you as I haven't seen in a very long time, perhaps more than I've ever seen.  Most of my students come here because something in particular gets them.  The paladins, the clerics, the rich, the poor, the elves, the dwarves, or even specifically, like Vaughn.  He hates his parents.  They give him everything and he loathes them for it.  So he comes here in secret to spite them.  It doesn't matter, he'll never be more than a warrior, but I can use that.  But, you, you're not like them.  You hate everyone ... everything.  You hate your fellow students, the Dismal Rage.   You hate dark elves and you hate our patron, Innoruuk.  I can see it in your eyes and hear it in your words.  You hate me.  You even hate yourself.&quot;<br>
<br>
Theresa glared at him, sullenly.  So what if it were all true, what was the point?<br>
<br>
&quot;And?&quot; she asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have no focus and you have no control.  Wendel was better, yes.  He has the training.  More important, though, he was controlled.  One word and all thought of defense was gone from you.  You only wanted to hurt him.  To unleash that pain and hate and rage onto someone.  I had you taken out of basic combat with the other students because the only thing you were doing with them was venting.  You're not learning.  You're just waiting for your turn to hurt someone.&quot;<br>
<br>
A long, silent moment passed between them.<br>
<br>
Softly, she asked, &quot;What do I do?&quot;<br>
<br>
Pietro nodded.  &quot;Don't give up your hate.  It is your strength.  It may help you survive when all else is gone.  But, you must learn to control it.  Remember, last week, when I executed that knight of Marr?&quot;<br>
<br>
He spat the name of the god of valor.  Theresa shrugged, waiting.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then you saw what remained of him.  If you can focus your hate, you can direct it as well.  You can channel it as pure agony into your foe.  It causes serious harm to even a healthy person, can finish off a wounded foe, or even kill a weaker one outright.  The Harm Touch is one of our greatest weapons.  It's also the first step on the true path of the Shadowknight.&quot;<br>
<br>
Theresa's eyes danced at the thought and she grinned.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are no where near that goal,&quot; he said, breaking her fantasy.<br>
<br>
&quot;You can't even focus on your weapon blows and you seriously lack any defensive skills.  In order to defeat your enemy, you must survive.  You can have all the hate in the world and a single sword blow can end your life.&quot;<br>
<br>
Sobered at the thought and realizing how idiotic she'd been in the weeks previous, Theresa nodded again.  Even more than, she hated the thought of ...<br>
<br>
&quot;You even hate me for pointing this out to you,&quot; Zarn chuckled.<br>
<br>
She smiled, not answering that question.  Instead, simply saying, &quot;I'll do it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Good.  Don't lose your edge.  Just control your anger and swallow your pride.  Whatever it takes to win ... remember that.&quot;<br>
<br>
Wiping blood away from her lip where he'd struck her, she said, &quot;I told you that if you hit me again, I would kill you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You're welcome to try, girl.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I also told you the name's Theresa.  And I think I'll wait ... until I'm ready.&quot;<br>
<br>
They both knew she wasn't kidding.  Zarn laughed again and walked away.<br>
<br>
&quot;Maybe you'll be the one, Theresa.&quot;<br>
____________________________________________________<br>
<br>
 Wendel Vaughn laughed mockingly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Me?  Teach you?&quot;<br>
<br>
Theresa nodded.  Her face bore the pleading look she'd often worn as a beggar child asking for coin.  It was hard not to express the contempt she actually felt.<br>
<br>
&quot;I need to learn and Brutol doesn't care to teach me.  Weak little girl, he says.  I have to learn somehow.  You've had so much training ...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And natural talent,&quot; he added.<br>
<br>
She agreed, &quot;Yes.  I know I can't hope to be that good, but if I'm just able to hold my own I won't end up back on the streets.&quot;  It was that easy.  Just like the people who gave her money as a child, he only needed her to say what he wanted to hear.  To feel good about himself.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, father's money has bought me the best.  I could help you, teach you, at least enough to pass Brutol's muster.&quot;  He paused, thinking.  &quot;Why should I?  Why should I care if some little street rat just ends up back where she belongs?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't know,&quot; she muttered.  Theresa tried looking helpless and needy.  Even the callous had sometimes given her money when she'd put on her most pathetic look.  It worked, she saw, as something dawned in his eyes.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes,&quot; he told her.  &quot;Yes, I can teach you.&quot;  His eyes crawled over her body and she saw something else there.  She shuddered.  &quot;I'll show you how to fight properly and I'll also show you how to do other things properly.  Hmm?  I'll make you into Brutol's little fighter and in return you will learn to be ... my ... little ...&quot;<br>
<br>
Theresa closed her eyes.  She knew what he was going to say and felt the anger coming.  Biting her lip, she fought it back.  Whatever it takes, Pietro said.  <br>
<br>
&quot; ... whore.&quot;<br>
<br>
Silence.  Then, weakly, “Okay.”<br>
<br>
Whatever it takes to win.<br>
____________________________________________________<br>
<br>
She knew he was asleep now.  His breathing had slowed from it's rapid pace to a shallow one.  He snored slightly.  More than anything, she wanted to kill him ... had wanted to the whole time he'd been ...<br>
<br>
Her mind raged.  The things she'd just done for him, things he'd done to her, the names he'd called her and the things he'd said.  It sickened her.  This is the life that Dad wanted for me.  To do this, probably every night, so that he could have his alcohol.  I'm glad I killed him.  I should kill Wendel.<br>
<br>
She hurt.  Worse than the pain, she felt ... broken.  Unclean.  Stupid, she thought, that a street rat would think that.  That stupid little girl.  She'd have never done something like this.  She’d have run and hid and starved and died.  Well, she's dead now.  Dead and gone and all that's left is ... me. Theresa buried her face in her pillow and cried.<br>
  <br>
It was the final death rattle of the girl she had been.  It was the birth of the woman she would come to be.<br>
